master.notes: Official Release #17This album was released in 1973.Initial UK vinyl issues used the distinct UK red DiscReet logo sleeve, with Euro-pressed & labeled disc. UK labeled pressings then quickly followed, with some sleeves over-stickered [url=http://s.pixogs.com/image/R-473291-1372689400-2250.jpeg]with artist's name[/url]."MS" prefixed run-out pressings, of US origin, have a noticeable audio difference to "K" prefixed pressings (UK & Euro) which, in comparison, have the left/right channels swapped.There is also a significant print difference on center spread of gatefolds. One version simply has 'sepia' & black print, the other has a solid brown/yellow color to the background areas. The two-headed character on the cover is [a2049627].

master.notes: This album was a long time coming, but once our conductors were ready to begin and embark on a full length opus, they ran into a problem. Having slimmed down to a two man production crew, Jay and Soulo were faced with the obstacle of not having a vocalist to rock over their tracks. On the other side of the coin though, back at the Sound Pro lab, new beats were being stacked up daily. The dilemma arose: How could they still get busy and drop a dope LP, minus a lead mc? Well, never the type to duck a challenge (or sit back and NOT make music), the beat fiends racked their brains in an effort to find a way two producers could put together a memorable lp. Could they do it? Was it even possible? Like Kris in 88', it had to get done... "by all means necessary". The solution? Create a concept for the album that would allow the Pro's to feature dope mc's, as well as a fly presentation to showcase their production. The blueprint was laid down and An Evening with the Sound Providers was born. [a82068], [a206415], [a66043], [a172035] and [a229159] we're all enlisted for the project. The end result was a finely executed, one night only performance with maestro's Jason Skills and Soulo. Add some of their favorite mc's, a host, and a dj for the night, and you'll be thankful your invitation arrived. The first LP finally dropped, and it was worth the wait.

master.notes: A record which chronicles Miles’ stunning journey from the acoustic to the electric!’.Recorded and released in 1969, the album ‘In a Silent Way’ was one of Miles Davis's most mysterious and elusive efforts. That was not only because the album, boasting one long track on each side, was so austerely understated, but also because it stood apart from the music that preceded it, the music Miles was performing in concert. Making use of multiple keyboardists (Herbie Hancock and Chick Corea on electric piano and Joe Zawinul on organ) Miles multiplies tones and melody lines and complicates textures. His mold-breaking band, also including Wayne Shorter on soprano saxophone, Tony Williams on drums and John McLaughlin on guitar, dips into rock and R&B, gospel and classical, electronics and creative editing.
